<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n10091d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n10" href="#n10091d">N10 (VI.B.16)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n10all.htm#n10091d"> 91(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> gite / foderum (billet)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Ainsi, les vieilles obligations du Cursus, justifi&eacute;es autrefois par l&apos;int&eacute;r&ecirc;t public, tendaient &agrave; se transformer en deux abus, qui ne sont pas les moins odieux en ce temps d&apos;anarchie, <mark>le droit de g&icirc;te et le foderum</mark>. Le droit de g&icirc;te &eacute;tait l&apos;hospitalit&eacute; due au prince et &agrave; sa suite, et m&ecirc;me &agrave; ses repr&eacute;sentants en mission, quand il passait ou s&eacute;journait sur les terres de son vassal; le plus riche pouvait &ecirc;tre ruin&eacute; par un s&eacute;jour &agrave; dessein prolong&eacute;: aussi la loi dut-elle intervenir pour en fixer autant que possible les conditions, la dur&eacute;e, et au besoin, le rachat. Le foderum, qui aurait d&ucirc; se borner &agrave; une r&eacute;quisition de fourrage pour les troupes, donnait lieu &agrave; mille exactions. <font color="green">[In this way the old obligations of the Cursus, that had been justified formerly by the public interest, tended to be transformed into two abuses, which were not the least odious in this time of anarchy, the right of lodging and the foderum. The right of lodging was the hospitality that was due to the prince and his following and even to his representatives on missions when they passed through or stayed on their lord&apos;s lands. Even the wealthiest could be ruined by an intentionally prolonged stay. Thus the law had to intervene to establish, as much as possible, the conditions, the duration, and if need be, the cost of buying one&apos;s way out. The foderum, which should have been limited to the requisition of fodder for the troops, led to a thousand extortions.]</font> <small> Arthur de Rothschild, <a name="ARHD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#ARHD"><cite title="source">Histoire de la poste</cite></a> (1876) 98-9</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
